ҳ—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@4d3fe4356886df65ded68ac317b12d878742d8cb567065332efd94a864636d26ІWorking with Lists‘ІWorking with ListsЪ:::tip

Lists are equivalent to the individual columns of tables. You can think of a list as essentially being a "one-column table" (with no column name). Thus, any command which operates on a column 
also
 operates on a list. For instance, 
[link: /commands/docs/where.md] ``where``
 can be used with lists:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[bell book candle] | where ($it =~ 'b')
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ bell в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ book в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
:::
’җҗЪ@Title: Working with Lists
Path: Working with Lists
Content:
:::tip

Lists are equivalent to the individual columns of tables. You can think of a list as essentially being a "one-column table" (with no column name). Thus, any command which operates on a column 
also
 operates on a list. For instance, 
[link: /commands/docs/where.md] ``where``
 can be used with lists:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[bell book candle] | where ($it =~ 'b')
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ bell в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ book в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
:::
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@5d2d293a078d5cc12acf8ac65d1b9dd67a536bcf9d8cf83e29d351f4f5bd546cІWorking with Lists‘®Creating listsЪҖA list is an ordered collection of values.

A list is created using square brackets surrounding values separated by spaces, linebreaks, and/or commas.

For example, 
``[foo bar baz]``
 or 
``[foo, bar, baz]``
.
::: tip

Nushell lists are similar to JSON arrays. The same 
``[ "Item1", "Item2", "Item3" ]``
 that represents a JSON array can also be used to create a Nushell list.

:::
’җҗЪёTitle: Working with Lists
Path: Creating lists
Content:
A list is an ordered collection of values.

A list is created using square brackets surrounding values separated by spaces, linebreaks, and/or commas.

For example, 
``[foo bar baz]``
 or 
``[foo, bar, baz]``
.
::: tip

Nushell lists are similar to JSON arrays. The same 
``[ "Item1", "Item2", "Item3" ]``
 that represents a JSON array can also be used to create a Nushell list.

:::
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@eaad10da557e204cfd6c38cd9506d885423eeea11ce71177d30313d70e3029d7ІWorking with Lists‘®Updating listsЪАWe can 
[link: /commands/docs/insert.md] ``insert``
 values into lists as they flow through the pipeline, for example let's insert the value 
``10``
 into the middle of a list:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1, 2, 3, 4] | insert 2 10
# => [1, 2, 10, 3, 4]

```
We can also use 
[link: /commands/docs/update.md] ``update``
 to replace the 2nd element with the value 
``10``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1, 2, 3, 4] | update 1 10
# => [1, 10, 3, 4]

```
’җҗЪшTitle: Working with Lists
Path: Updating lists
Content:
We can 
[link: /commands/docs/insert.md] ``insert``
 values into lists as they flow through the pipeline, for example let's insert the value 
``10``
 into the middle of a list:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1, 2, 3, 4] | insert 2 10
# => [1, 2, 10, 3, 4]

```
We can also use 
[link: /commands/docs/update.md] ``update``
 to replace the 2nd element with the value 
``10``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1, 2, 3, 4] | update 1 10
# => [1, 10, 3, 4]

```
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@7b150dac94dd8537c8c9800056ebf43792b89fdb08011a9e14b62ffca6758fa0ІWorking with Lists‘Щ"Removing or Adding Items from ListЪтIn addition to 
[link: /commands/docs/insert.md] ``insert``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/update.md] ``update``
, we also have 
[link: /commands/docs/prepend.md] ``prepend``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/append.md] ``append``
. These let you insert to the beginning of a list or at the end of the list, respectively.
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [yellow green]
let colors = ($colors | prepend red)
let colors = ($colors | append purple)
let colors = ($colors ++ ["blue"])
let colors = (["black"] ++ $colors)
$colors
# => [black red yellow green purple blue]

```
In case you want to remove items from list, there are many ways. 
[link: /commands/docs/skip.md] ``skip``
 allows you skip first rows from input, while 
[link: /commands/docs/drop.md] ``drop``
 allows you to skip specific numbered rows from end of list.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red yellow green purple]
let colors = ($colors | skip 1)
let colors = ($colors | drop 2)
$colors
# => [yellow]

```
We also have 
[link: /commands/docs/last.md] ``last``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/first.md] ``first``
 which allow you to 
[link: /commands/docs/take.md] ``take``
 from the end or beginning of the list, respectively.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red yellow green purple black magenta]
let colors = ($colors | last 3)
$colors
# => [purple black magenta]

```
And from the beginning of a list,
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [yellow green purple]
let colors = ($colors | first 2)
$colors
# => [yellow green]

```
’җҗЪ>Title: Working with Lists
Path: Removing or Adding Items from List
Content:
In addition to 
[link: /commands/docs/insert.md] ``insert``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/update.md] ``update``
, we also have 
[link: /commands/docs/prepend.md] ``prepend``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/append.md] ``append``
. These let you insert to the beginning of a list or at the end of the list, respectively.
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [yellow green]
let colors = ($colors | prepend red)
let colors = ($colors | append purple)
let colors = ($colors ++ ["blue"])
let colors = (["black"] ++ $colors)
$colors
# => [black red yellow green purple blue]

```
In case you want to remove items from list, there are many ways. 
[link: /commands/docs/skip.md] ``skip``
 allows you skip first rows from input, while 
[link: /commands/docs/drop.md] ``drop``
 allows you to skip specific numbered rows from end of list.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red yellow green purple]
let colors = ($colors | skip 1)
let colors = ($colors | drop 2)
$colors
# => [yellow]

```
We also have 
[link: /commands/docs/last.md] ``last``
 and 
[link: /commands/docs/first.md] ``first``
 which allow you to 
[link: /commands/docs/take.md] ``take``
 from the end or beginning of the list, respectively.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red yellow green purple black magenta]
let colors = ($colors | last 3)
$colors
# => [purple black magenta]

```
And from the beginning of a list,
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [yellow green purple]
let colors = ($colors | first 2)
$colors
# => [yellow green]

```
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@c5721d6451e6f0938a437cf58ff0247030538225df1ef0053405835d93c02e38ІWorking with Lists‘№Using the Spread OperatorЪҜTo append one or more lists together, optionally with values interspersed in between, you can also use the

[link: /book/operators#spread-operator] spread operator
 (
``...``
):
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let x = [1 2]
[
  ...$x
  3
  ...(4..7 | take 2)
]
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
’җҗЪтTitle: Working with Lists
Path: Using the Spread Operator
Content:
To append one or more lists together, optionally with values interspersed in between, you can also use the

[link: /book/operators#spread-operator] spread operator
 (
``...``
):
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let x = [1 2]
[
  ...$x
  3
  ...(4..7 | take 2)
]
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@0a754470171e75939f2e2c6acca1cb43b70ecfb16826e0c073d09074a0e3f2eeІWorking with Lists‘ҙIterating over ListsЪpTo iterate over the items in a list, use the 
[link: /commands/docs/each.md] ``each``
 command with a 
[link: types_of_data.html#blocks] block

of Nu code that specifies what to do to each item. The block parameter (e.g. 
``|elt|``
 in 
``{ |elt| print $elt }``
) is the current list

item, but the 
[link: /commands/docs/enumerate.md] ``enumerate``
 filter can be used to provide 
``index``
 and 
``item``
 values if needed. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let names = [Mark Tami Amanda Jeremy]
$names | each { |elt| $"Hello, ($elt)!" }
# Outputs "Hello, Mark!" and three more similar lines.

$names | enumerate | each { |elt| $"($elt.index + 1) - ($elt.item)" }
# Outputs "1 - Mark", "2 - Tami", etc.

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/where.md] ``where``
 command can be used to create a subset of a list, effectively filtering the list based on a condition.
The following example gets all the colors whose names end in "e".
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red orange yellow green blue purple]
$colors | where ($it | str ends-with 'e')
# The block passed to `where` must evaluate to a boolean.
# This outputs the list [orange blue purple].

```
In this example, we keep only values higher than 
``7``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let scores = [7 10 8 6 7]
$scores | where $it > 7 # [10 8]

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/reduce.md] ``reduce``
 command computes a single value from a list.

It uses a block which takes 2 parameters: the current item (conventionally named 
``elt``
) and an accumulator

(conventionally named 
``acc``
). To specify an initial value for the accumulator, use the 
``--fold``
 (
``-f``
) flag.

To change 
``elt``
 to have 
``index``
 and 
``item``
 values, use the 
[link: /commands/docs/enumerate.md] ``enumerate``
 filter.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let scores = [3 8 4]
$"total = ($scores | reduce { |elt, acc| $acc + $elt })" # total = 15

$"total = ($scores | math sum)" # easier approach, same result

$"product = ($scores | reduce --fold 1 { |elt, acc| $acc * $elt })" # product = 96

$scores | enumerate | reduce --fold 0 { |elt, acc| $acc + $elt.index * $elt.item } # 0*3 + 1*8 + 2*4 = 16

```
’җҗЪ®Title: Working with Lists
Path: Iterating over Lists
Content:
To iterate over the items in a list, use the 
[link: /commands/docs/each.md] ``each``
 command with a 
[link: types_of_data.html#blocks] block

of Nu code that specifies what to do to each item. The block parameter (e.g. 
``|elt|``
 in 
``{ |elt| print $elt }``
) is the current list

item, but the 
[link: /commands/docs/enumerate.md] ``enumerate``
 filter can be used to provide 
``index``
 and 
``item``
 values if needed. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let names = [Mark Tami Amanda Jeremy]
$names | each { |elt| $"Hello, ($elt)!" }
# Outputs "Hello, Mark!" and three more similar lines.

$names | enumerate | each { |elt| $"($elt.index + 1) - ($elt.item)" }
# Outputs "1 - Mark", "2 - Tami", etc.

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/where.md] ``where``
 command can be used to create a subset of a list, effectively filtering the list based on a condition.
The following example gets all the colors whose names end in "e".
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red orange yellow green blue purple]
$colors | where ($it | str ends-with 'e')
# The block passed to `where` must evaluate to a boolean.
# This outputs the list [orange blue purple].

```
In this example, we keep only values higher than 
``7``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let scores = [7 10 8 6 7]
$scores | where $it > 7 # [10 8]

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/reduce.md] ``reduce``
 command computes a single value from a list.

It uses a block which takes 2 parameters: the current item (conventionally named 
``elt``
) and an accumulator

(conventionally named 
``acc``
). To specify an initial value for the accumulator, use the 
``--fold``
 (
``-f``
) flag.

To change 
``elt``
 to have 
``index``
 and 
``item``
 values, use the 
[link: /commands/docs/enumerate.md] ``enumerate``
 filter.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let scores = [3 8 4]
$"total = ($scores | reduce { |elt, acc| $acc + $elt })" # total = 15

$"total = ($scores | math sum)" # easier approach, same result

$"product = ($scores | reduce --fold 1 { |elt, acc| $acc * $elt })" # product = 96

$scores | enumerate | reduce --fold 0 { |elt, acc| $acc + $elt.index * $elt.item } # 0*3 + 1*8 + 2*4 = 16

```
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@0d75cd5ab3fde68f7208498f6ba0d94a8dfbfc20ced0fcd4a2292edaaddb4c33ІWorking with Lists‘ІAccessing the ListЪ	ж::: tip Note

The following is a basic overview. For a more in-depth discussion of this topic, see the chapter, 
[link: /book/navigating_structured_data.md] Navigating and Accessing Structured Data
.

:::
To access a list item at a given index, use the 
``$name.index``
 form where 
``$name``
 is a variable that holds a list.
For example, the second element in the list below can be accessed with 
``$names.1``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let names = [Mark Tami Amanda Jeremy]
$names.1 # gives Tami

```
If the index is in some variable 
``$index``
 we can use the 
``get``
 command to extract the item from the list.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let names = [Mark Tami Amanda Jeremy]
let index = 1
$names | get $index # gives Tami

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/length.md] ``length``
 command returns the number of items in a list.

For example, 
``[red green blue] | length``
 outputs 
``3``
.
The 
[link: /commands/docs/is-empty.md] ``is-empty``
 command determines whether a string, list, or table is empty.

It can be used with lists as follows:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red green blue]
$colors | is-empty # false

let colors = []
$colors | is-empty # true

```
The 
``in``
 and 
``not-in``
 operators are used to test whether a value is in a list. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red green blue]
'blue' in $colors # true
'yellow' in $colors # false
'gold' not-in $colors # true

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/any.md] ``any``
 command determines if any item in a list

matches a given condition.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red green blue]
# Do any color names end with "e"?
$colors | any {|elt| $elt | str ends-with "e" } # true

# Is the length of any color name less than 3?
$colors | any {|elt| ($elt | str length) < 3 } # false

let scores = [3 8 4]
# Are any scores greater than 7?
$scores | any {|elt| $elt > 7 } # true

# Are any scores odd?
$scores | any {|elt| $elt mod 2 == 1 } # true

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/all.md] ``all``
 command determines if every item in a list

matches a given condition.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let colors = [red green blue]
# Do all color names end with "e"?
$colors | all {|elt| $elt | str ends-with "e" } # false

# Is the length of all color names greater than or equal to 3?
$colors | all {|elt| ($elt | str length) >= 3 } # true

let scores = [3 8 4]
# Are all scores greater than 7?
$scores | all {|elt| $elt > 7 } # false

# Are all scores even?
$scores | all {|elt| $elt mod 2 == 0 } # false

```
