# Are all scores greater than 7?
$scores | all {|elt| $elt > 7 } # false

# Are all scores even?
$scores | all {|elt| $elt mod 2 == 0 } # false

```
—ЩQarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/working_with_lists.mdЩ@48a2350c4e1086c5caada107be1e90059c3e008a4ce1fc7d67930f22a344aec8ІWorking with Lists‘іConverting the ListЪThe 
[link: /commands/docs/flatten.md] ``flatten``
 command creates a new list from an existing list

by adding items in nested lists to the top-level list.

This can be called multiple times to flatten lists nested at any depth.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1 [2 3] 4 [5 6]] | flatten # [1 2 3 4 5 6]

[[1 2] [3 [4 5 [6 7 8]]]] | flatten | flatten | flatten # [1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8]

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/wrap.md] ``wrap``
 command converts a list to a table. Each list value will

be converted to a separate row with a single column:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let zones = [UTC CET Europe/Moscow Asia/Yekaterinburg]

# Show world clock for selected time zones
$zones | wrap 'Zone' | upsert Time {|row| (date now | date to-timezone $row.Zone | format date '%Y.%m.%d %H:%M')}

```
’җҗЪZTitle: Working with Lists
Path: Converting the List
Content:
The 
[link: /commands/docs/flatten.md] ``flatten``
 command creates a new list from an existing list

by adding items in nested lists to the top-level list.

This can be called multiple times to flatten lists nested at any depth.

For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[1 [2 3] 4 [5 6]] | flatten # [1 2 3 4 5 6]

[[1 2] [3 [4 5 [6 7 8]]]] | flatten | flatten | flatten # [1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8]

```
The 
[link: /commands/docs/wrap.md] ``wrap``
 command converts a list to a table. Each list value will

be converted to a separate row with a single column:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let zones = [UTC CET Europe/Moscow Asia/Yekaterinburg]

# Show world clock for selected time zones
$zones | wrap 'Zone' | upsert Time {|row| (date now | date to-timezone $row.Zone | format date '%Y.%m.%d %H:%M')}

```
